stabilising overall price levels as the top priority of our controls and keep the direction of macro-economic adjustments unchanged,\" Wen said today in comments reported on the central government's website. He had said in March that the ruling is worried that a continuing rise in food prices could result in public protests.\nWen said the government would boost the supply of to keep the price of pork stable, the price of pork being the major contributor to China's food inflation index and the most closely watched item on it.\n\"If they signal any comfort with inflation, and inflation is as high as it is now, they could create an environment in which people would panic, and they can have a real problem on their hands,\" said Tim Condon, Asian researcher at . \nAs markets worried about the news of Chinese inflation as well as concerns about the , oil dropped below US$95 a barrel today. "}
